The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I did .
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
Still, we're missing something here-- a virtual operator to make the classics go down.
He might not be gone long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
Moreover, this was confirmed by the CNU, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges may lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that's really willing to go into battle.
This may seem paradoxical, but we have three cell networks and a penetration rate of well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to play on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák has often pointed this out, having said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a traditional operator with its own network seems to have little chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there's another option - a virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market led to a significant price reduction, which was then also met by traditional operators.
And before the arrival of hamsters like Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, there were voices in the UK that were similar to ours.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
Besides, we don't have to go far to find examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet decided whether the measure is compatible with the internal market.
In this world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, but this is often offset by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheaply as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a raw target group can be a pretty good move.
This operator is specifically targeting men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and trust", says David Seibertz, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual operator.
It's hard to say if a similar concept to Poland could catch on here.
The Commission notes that the Czech Republic has not yet adopted a decision on the compatibility of the measure with the internal market.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of the range of services it offers.'
No chance in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about expanding this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not looking too promising.
It is more likely that Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region", Jana Studničková, a spokeswoman for Penta's financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
The Commission therefore concludes that the measure is imputable to the State.
Rather, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor emerges.
GTS Novera has long been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator, and thus wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
'We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
