The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet established the existence of a market economy investor principle.
Miroslav Čepický says: 'We are open to potential virtual operators, especially in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
That's what we consider the most beneficial from a customer perspective.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet.'
Responsible authorities - one-handed with operators
The mobile operators' behaviour is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
Why, then, facilitate the entry of such a competitor?
The fact that operators can pull together when they want something is also shown by the tension around the creation of the U:phone.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on the CTU came at the time of the creation of U:phone by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information on the ČTU website.
But now, it's U:fon that's the argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemr commented: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on it and in particular on its services.'
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the complete indifference of the Czech regulatory authorities is striking.
This is not just the position of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere in competition.
These are exclusively the responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Competition (OCC).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not of sufficient interest to traditional operators', said Kristián Chalupa from the EEAS's External Relations Department in response to our question.
This statement from the operators' representatives is not surprising.
This is a big step forward for an agency that is supposed to represent consumers' interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market.
In particular, as Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries where virtual operators are common, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower mobile phone prices".
However, it is clear that the pressure to correct the market environment and the decrease in prices is not in the interests of the GOC.
What's really shocking about the whole case is the touching consensus of the three cell phone operators that comes from their response.
