Prague MHD will be bringing in a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will go down in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, tram and buses with an electronic ticket in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
It can buy about 100,000 people who own an OpenCard chip card right now.
Passengers can buy and have their 30-day, 90-day and annual vouchers (valid from 1 January 2009) uploaded to their chip cards at the Transport Enterprise's information centres and workplaces at the Museum, Bridge, Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
Coupons can be purchased online from yesterday on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
Over 400 customers had used the service by this afternoon.
Those who start using online shopping can finally forget about the sales windows in subway stations, where they have had to regularly stand in long lines for paper tickets.
They buy a coupon online and have it uploaded to their Opencard card at one of the 13 City Library branches.
"At these places, passengers have a counter with trained staff to help them with their online shopping and to upload the voucher to their card", said Martin Opatrný, a spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to download electronic Opencard vouchers from the self-service machines installed in several metro halls.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, resembling ticket signs, and passengers may have noticed them at the underground stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the city, but by the end of the year there should be 80", added the Cautious One.
The coupon checks the driver's seat automatically
The machines, which will be operational tomorrow, are simple to operate.
You just insert an Opencard chip card into them and the prepaid coupon loads itself into them.
Electronic coupons will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding areas.
That is, on suburban trains and buses with the number 300 to 499, which are mainly used by residents of central Bohemian municipalities.
"On trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport system, the drivers are equipped with card readers to check the time and band validity of the tickets", explained ticket inspector Filip Drápal of Ropid, an organization that compiles Prague's public transport timetables.
Suburban buses have card readers built into the driver's locker.
The Opencard is therefore not only required to be shown to the driver when boarding, but also to be affixed to a designated spot on the side of the register.
This will allow the driver to check the validity of the downloaded coupons.
"If a passenger needs to check the validity of the downloaded coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information", he added.
Passengers who do not use the buses and do not remember when their voucher expires can go back to the vending machines where the vouchers are loaded onto their card.
Here, information about the validity of their documents is displayed on the instrument display.
Sudetenland wanted a referendum on the United States .
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 asked for the incorporation of the Schumacher Region into the United States.
It is clear from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States.
It was reported that in 1945 a group of Sudeten Germans appealed to the President of the United States for such a request.
This is shown, among other things, by a letter that was preserved in a private archive and is now in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans from Czechoslovakia request in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Schumauer Dörfer" - seized by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and want to be sure that the American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", says the letter, signed "People who care about the fate of the Schumacher".
Since the annexation of Czechoslovakia supposedly gives the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national character - only hope for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protectorate over Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that, despite the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would grant this territory to some foreign state that oppresses and discourages minorities and has done nothing, nothing at all to help the Allies win", the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly fear of the vengeance of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States were supposed to question the minds of the Germans of Schumacher, all he had to do was hold a referendum in Schumacher County on whether its inhabitants wanted to become part of the United States or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a bit naive in today's knowledge of postwar history, some historians believe it aptly reflects the expectations of Sudeten Germans at the time.
Although the Czech Germans must have at least suspected that this would mean their expulsion from the republic, few of them even considered such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
