Rats have feelings too
When a rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that they too are afraid?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings.
But how could we verify that they feel the same way when they behave the same way as we do?
The online magazine "Edge" has been publishing contributions from prominent scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else has not been able to prove, if we can't prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But once we start to look at another species and open up to questions of perception or consciousness in general, we enter into a very incompatible terrain because the hardware doesn't match.
When in danger, the rat will do what many other animals do: it will pretend to be dead, flee, or attack.
Humans behave similarly, which some scientists have concluded is a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal experience.
This is partly because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always involve the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive or management functions).
This vast area is far more developed in humans than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature may be the linguistic nature of man: Because so much of his perception is related to language, consciousness is often said to depend on it.
In this case, we could rule out animals.
But even if consciousness didn't matter to language, it would certainly be affected by language, so animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably be different from most states of consciousness in our own.
That's why it's difficult to know what consciousness might look like in other animals.
When, as something intrinsic and subjective, it can't be measured or, because of the special hardware, analyzed from our own experience, we face major problems exploring it.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study the processes in the animal mind regardless of their content, and that's exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially in the case of visualization.
But this approach, which was pioneered by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both can be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the importance of the nonfrontal cortex for visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I'm guessing it's because an emotional system like the fear system is activated in the brain that's aware of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is a mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of a defense system located in the brain (or its effects, such as bodily reactions) exploits working memory.
And from this angle, sensation is closely linked to those areas of the cortex that are characteristic of primates, and especially humans.
And in connection with the nature of language, there is a subtle gradation of perception, because we can use words and grammar to distinguish and categorize states to attribute to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the cortex and brainstem areas devoted to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could easily share the feelings of many animal species.
I can't argue with that, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what seems to us to be fear in rats and humans is likely felt by both organisms in the same way: But how can it be verified, Pankseep says, that rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach fleeing danger - does it feel fear?
In my view, mere similarity in behavior cannot prove similarity in experience.
True, the neural comparison takes us further: Rats and humans have similar brain strains, whereas cockroaches have no brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if we could prove that in humans, how would we want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I don't really know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I'm more interested in emotional behavior than in emotional perception in rats.
Anyway, in this case, we can expect to see improvements at the neural level if we measure the same thing in rats and humans.
Just as I don't study language and consciousness in a rat, I don't study feelings, because I don't know if they exist.
It may be considered shortsighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throw myself against a wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
