The debate on bilingualism: immersing yourself in English
In this edition of Focus on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss the attitude of candidates to bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a California academic and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is co-author of "Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools".
Effectively reaching the Hispanic electorate is a tricky business.
Barack Obama's education agenda just proves that.
The Obama campaign notes that "African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students", which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, the Obama education agenda specifically promotes, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for those who are still learning English.
The question for Barack Obama, however, remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is not stronger than his interest in reducing performance gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in East Los Angeles County.
The vast majority of the students at this school are Hispanic from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
And yet, in the 2008 state math tests, they got the top score of an incredible 100 percent of fourth graders.
Almost as amazingly, 93 percent of fourth graders scored high on the state's English and literature tests.
This incredible success was achieved by a different method than the one Obama prefers.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of ability and no-excuse approach.
Furthermore, and Obama should note this, according to Linda Mikels, the head of Sixth Street, the school's approach to teaching English to newcomers is "totally immersive".
The immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me, "We had a huge success with one brand-new student from Mexico -- you'd walk into a classroom in 12 months and not know which one it was".
"It works", she declared, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with high percentages of Hispanic and English learners should look like?
The results the school achieves should be taken for granted, but the educational agenda of his own party (the National Education Association is a longtime advocate of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education cloud Obama's predictions of an answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue when he said that people should stop worrying about "English-only" laws.
Instead, "you should make sure your children speak Spanish", he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance gaps, he should be thinking about the educational models that work, rather than ridiculing and trivializing them.
