The reckoned Gebreselassie has improved his world record
Haile Gebreselassie of Ethiopia once again showed why he is considered by many to be the greatest distance runner of all time when he broke his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday, becoming the first man to run a 26.2-mile race in under two hours and four minutes.
By winning the pleasantly flat course in 2:03:59, he beat his previous time of 2:04:26 from last year in Berlin by 27 seconds.
Gebreselassie, 35, set the 26th world record in a career that is truly incredibly long - he broke the world record or at least is the world champion at all distances from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month Gebreselassie missed the Beijing Olympic marathon because he feared - perhaps too much in retrospect - that air pollution would aggravate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In near-perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - he won Sunday's Gebreselassie with a lightning-fast average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
With track runners like Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya moving to longer distances, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the past decade since Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil won in Berlin in a time of 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters that he had a calf cramp two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
The break obviously stimulated him more than it delayed.
"I'm so happy", Gebreselassie said to reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago and I was a little hesitant today, but everything was fine".
He was also criticized - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for allegedly over-planning his races, generally avoiding world marathon top finishes, relying on drivers as if it were a race on a track, and putting world records above the sense of competition.
But this criticism can hardly diminish Gebreselassie's tremendous running skills.
Maintained in pace by four Kenyans, Gebreselassie reached the halfway mark in 1:02:04.
After the drivers passed out, Gebreselassie was constantly being overtaken by two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi.
Just three miles before the Gebreselassie finish, he took a last-ditch run to Kwambai, who then finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, finished the year with the seventh fastest time in history at 2:19:19.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliff of Great Britain.
The 36-year-old Mikitinenko surprisingly won the London Marathon last spring in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games because of what was described as a back injury, but recovered and won in Berlin, improving her personal best by almost five minutes in the third marathon she ever ran.
She ran the race smartly and thoughtfully, running a long lead on four Ethiopian and Kenyan runners and then overtaking them at about 18 1⁄2 miles.
Askalefa Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and obstacles of black life in a segregated city
Hidden among the sprawling theme parks of Greater Orlando, miles from all the glitter, noise and giganticness, lies a quiet city that is alive with the pride and the challenge of African-American life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city to be incorporated and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred browns, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of queue, two schools, and no jail".
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Eatonville Festival of Dawn! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The town she described remains out of the picture, even though she made it a tourist stopover by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression.
It is still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he does not know what he is missing".
Even today, in a year when black presidential candidate Senator Barack Obama is calling for an open discussion about race, many residents remain wary of the gaze of strangers.
"We're very careful about how our story is told", says Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the area and a member of the city's oldest parish.
"It has to be right".
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It's both a historical model of black upward mobility and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It's a literary center, but it's also a shadowy example of the Southern rural black culture -- sometimes despised, sometimes praised -- that came out of American slavery.
It's not surprising that the locals are both proud and protective.
And the concerns about the image of Eatonville really didn't start until Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced the world to her hometown through heartfelt books full of dialects such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
Five paragraphs of a Florida tour guide turned the town a short distance from Highway 17, which runs through the often-drifting downtown area of Florida, into a stage for black history and human drama.
With the big drum in life and literature in the air, Hurston introduced readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road", she wrote, "is a white, brown, modern public school with well-kept courtyards and playgrounds, always looked after by Howard Miller, though he is not very good at reading or writing".
She also mentioned Dash's new widowed husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits in a clock hotel".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to local government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This was obviously not typical of Fodor's publishing.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora told it like it was", says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, a member of the Johnson Girls, whom Hurston immortalized by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it", she added.
Hurston is still remembered as a cypriot freak who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of her rushes into town were unannounced in a huge Chevy, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still prides itself on its decent dress.
Most of the inhabitants were fascinated, Franklin said, but many were reluctant.
"The people of Dawn have always been happy to see", Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back porch overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or major public readings in Eatonville.
"I think they didn't understand her significance to the world or her legacy at all", said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography, Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 1980's.
Orange County officials wanted to run a five-lane freeway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-lane highway.
Orlando's erosion has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, among other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle to interracialise brought hatred to the doorstep of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at people who were sitting on the side", Franklin said.
"We actually had a lady here who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration, calling its decision in Brown v. Board of Education "more offensive than glorifying to my race".
Residents now say that desegregation of schools, while positive in some areas, has diminished cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the youth.
"Black kids were used to hugging - I remember - you hug your teacher in the morning, you hug your teacher in the evening", said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You don't hug your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean there's a cultural barrier", Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many other Neale Hurston Zoras - black writers, actors, and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with reckless self-confidence and quotes like "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand that".
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, the highly praised biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway came onto bookstore shelves, re-classifying her as an American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was rediscovering the lights of the ramp.
Hurston's former neighbors now saw her as a savior.
To show what can happen to their highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and many return to celebrate every January.
The state backed out of the highway proposal after a few years.
"The five streams of the highway have revived, you could say they have really set off, a real civic pride", Nathiri said.
Boyd said it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the local church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to reevaluate their past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes seem like a backwater in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, 90 percent are black.)
Strangers who come to Eatonville seeking the history and significance of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission, and certain things - like the murals in Eatonville's oldest church, painted by white people and showing blacks in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, confident teacher who loves red, still fear that their isolated community will be misunderstood.
And as the Hurston Festival grew, so did the local pride.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, but no better, no worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, has a heartfelt love of the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for local government or the police, which he says he could use some help with.
And even the younger ones, like the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they pass by, think, 'Hmm, this town is nothing compared to the others,'" said Alondra Kenon recently after church on a Sunday.
"But if you really stop and look at the history for a moment, it's a very nice town".
Here in New York , we all speak fluent financial
Nothing has changed at first glance.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from newsstands and giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the glass beehive of offices above them, every day the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York have their worst "bad day at the office" since the 1929 crash.
The couriers are still rocking metal trolleys on the sidewalks and carrying muffin makers to the breakfast meeting.
The Spanish still move between the towers, carrying, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts hanging from the pendulums on their backs.
Office rats still waiting in line for their morning bagel at street food stands, and it's still impossible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between 4:00 and 7:00 p.m.
It didn't look like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this assignment to coincide with a late afternoon siesta at my local JPMorgan Chase branch, there were already about 20 people waiting in line.
Not in front of the cash register to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of the ledger where older customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's mixed-use store and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker", came for the same reason I did.
But unlike me, they've already taken their savings from smaller banks in places where they came from, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Staten Island.
They took money from thrift banks, credit unions, and those types of savings banks that have branches in only one state and that claim to care for their customers like family.
In the past year, 15 of these banks have quietly gone bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, was trying to find a buyer.
The office and store workers who were standing in front of me, afraid of another collapse, were moving their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the bailouts on Wall Street.
Average New Yorkers have learned their financials in the last week.
Some woman at my local Chinese supermarket was on the phone and talking to Lehman Brothers, that failed bank, and her skinny CEO Dick Fuld with such familiarity as if she was gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed housekeeper of my tenant's, about 50, changed the subject of our usual conversation-- Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she said: "I have my savings in money market funds now.
I moved it. I'm not taking any chances".
Muslim graves desecrated after Austria's right-wing breakdown
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, from the Austrian right-wing Free Party and Filip Dewinter from the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party take part in a demonstration presented by the organization Cities Against Islamization in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs similar to traffic signs that show mosques crossed by a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that far-right parties made huge gains in the general election.
More than 90 graves in the cemetery in Traun, near Linz, were badly damaged between Friday night and this morning, and police believe it was an organized act.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols on some of the graves, such as the Star of David, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to cover up the motives of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It's not clear if this incident was connected to the election in any way.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by reports of the desecration, which comes as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan draws to a close.
Austria, meanwhile, is entering a cycle of soul searching after the right-wing swing in yesterday's general election.
The two far-right parties, which collectively won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Free Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, waged a fierce anti-immigration campaign, and some of their slogans were condemned by critics as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the Free Party, which won over 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against scarves and burqas, and even expressed his dislike of foods that were perceived to be related to Islam.
