"To capture the true character, I photograph the master off-scene".
No heels, no calls or costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from the focus of interpretation, will achieve the relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On one side, an artist.
On the other, a human.
They're indiscriminate, if you leave privacy out, in those moments away from the audience -- where you can see a gesture of intimacy, the depth of a glance caught in a flash, or the passionate gesture of hands that are casual because they're not going to step on stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates the theatrical performance of "Flamenco-people" with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer assembles a unique iconography of flamenco from different backgrounds.
The exhibition, which is part of the Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca (Flamenco Photography Month) programme, "reflects the ever-growing international importance of flamenco", says the author, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people, but when you look at the photographs, you find that they are not typical images of artists on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists who are able to bring passion, sadness, joy... to the stage and completely captivate the audience.
It's not necessary to take a picture on stage to capture the personality of these artists.
He carries his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco greats.
Fascinated by the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer began a long journey of portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on the record camera in 1997.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The use of different stylistic means contradicts the classical basis of the picture and gives it a contemporary spirit, an idea that Bauer himself says is reflected in flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which never ceases to surprise and evolve".
What draws the audience is not the performance of the dance, the singing, or the play itself but the personality and character of the performer.
Finding the moment to encounter the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perceiving, being and experiencing, was and is a constant in the work presented during these days in the El Fotomata gallery.
This selection of almost seventy photographed artists is made up of well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and will soon be published as a book, which will contain the exhibited portraits.
Two years ago, Bauer's passion for portraiture led him to the idea of repeating it in "Portraits of Sports Veterans" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from that of "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "photographing people, getting to know them and being able to step into their lives for a moment, whether it's longer or just a short one - that's my passion.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or clash with people, personalities that you sometimes don't even know or that only give you a few minutes to photograph.
Despite similar circumstances, I always try to make my images come true as a photographer".
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco artists entitled "Flamenco-people" is on display at the Galeria El Fotómata at 20 de la Mata Street, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
