Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install an "alcolock"
The Home Office requires drivers with three administrative penalties for DUI to have a system installed in their vehicle to prevent them from starting the car while drunk or not breathing.
The proposal was made public in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Prosecutor General's Office, which states that it is a pilot project for a period of one year.
The aim is to get drivers back behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to undergo a road re-education course.
The experience will involve the National Road Safety Authority (NTSO) as well as the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Motor Vehicle Safety (FITSA).
Statistics show that between 30 and 75 percent of drivers who are accused of drunk driving more than once will get behind the wheel again.
Alcolock should prevent this as it is a vehicle-mounted system that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe first or if an alcohol concentration is recorded above the permissible level.
The price is over 1000 euros and the offender will have to pay for it.
A study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that the number of offences for vehicles equipped with this device fell by 65% in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that it could save 115 lives each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its introduction, since legislation can be implemented in the usual way, the necessary adjustment of the penal provisions requires an amendment of the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has been tested on some commercial and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a proposal by the PSOE (Spanish Socialist Workers' Party) to install the system in school buses, as it is in France.
