Sleep-talking
Some children talk at night.
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something about the day before, but the kids who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may scare you, but it's actually nothing.
It's a harmless sleep disorder called somnolence.
It's quite common, especially in children and teenagers.
I'm sure many of you have been told that he spoke in his sleep last night.
This may occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with a high fever) or more regularly (every day, once a week, once every few months, etc.) and the child does not remember anything the next day.
There's not one single reason for her coming.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (night-time urination), or sleepwalking, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful situations, or a heightened mood.
In any case, it is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears also varies.
The child may speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or vice versa (screams, cries, long speeches, etc.).
In cases where it is strong, it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if there is a problem that causes the child to have a high level of anxiety and manifests itself in this way.
We said it's a harmless disorder, so it's not treated unless it's associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (like if it's associated with apnea syndrome or chronic stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to disturb the child too much before he goes to sleep.
So seek out peaceful games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who are given work to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
If you have sleepwalking, try to stay calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything.
Useful Advice
Don't be him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you're interrupting his sleep.
Even though he talks, he's sleeping, and therefore resting.
Remember, if you repeatedly find that your child seems to be very distressed, it may be wise to seek counsel or to find out what is causing the child's anxiety.
If he understands what he is saying (which is not always the case), avoid the temptation to question him and extract information from him.
It's no use, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
Furthermore, you can hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming about or why he is saying it, so be very careful about how you interpret the information and draw conclusions.
Never tell a child that you can ask him his secret at night.
Not for fun.
It causes a lot of anxiety.
Don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's just an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
