The world's fourth largest aircraft manufacturer, Embraer, is maintaining its 2008 delivery forecast with 215 aircraft delivered, its president Fredrico Fleury Curado confirmed.
In the first half of the year, the manufacturer delivered 97 aircraft.
The Brazilian manufacturer has a lot of promise from the Chinese market, especially given the range of its aircraft from 30 to 120 seats.
To date, Embraer has delivered 41 aircraft to Chinese customers over a period of eight years.
AIG is reportedly considering a 15% asset sale.
American International Group, an insurer that has been bailed out by the U.S. monetary authorities, is considering selling more than 15 percent of its assets to pay off $85 billion in down payments, reports the Financial Times on Sunday.
AIG is prepared to consider selling off most of its non-life insurance business in the international field and its pension business in the United States, the newspaper said, citing sources familiar with the ongoing negotiations.
France Télécom's comments were therefore rejected.
No confirmatory statement could be obtained from AIG.
The assets to be divested by AIG include its air leasing subsidiary International Lease Financial Corp., its 59% stake in the insurer Transatlantic Holdings, as well as its real estate portfolio and private equity investments, the FT adds.
