Paris: analysis of the historic morning meeting
The New York Stock Exchange fell to a record low on Monday after the House of Representatives rejected Paulson's bank bailout plan: The Dow Jones lost 6.98%, an unprecedented loss approaching 800 points, and the Nasdaq 9.14%.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA) has fallen 777.68 points to 10,365.45.
The biggest drop in its history (by 684.81 points) was recorded on 17 September 2001, the day trading resumed after the terrorist attacks of 11 September.
The Nasdaq index with a predominantly technology component lost 199,61 points to 1 983,73 at the close of trading and the extended Standard & Poor's 500 index fell by 8,81 % (i.e. 106,85 points) to 1 106,55 points.
Dejected from the start of the session, Wall Street has literally collapsed after the House of Representatives unexpectedly rejected a bank bailout plan that was supposed to allow markets to regain some stability.
By a vote of 228 to 205, the House of Representatives has refused to grant Secretary of the Treasury Henry Paulson the funds he requested.
Nearly two out of three Republicans rejected his plan.
"It's a bad signal to the market that Congress is not able to pass a plan", believes FTN Financial's Lindsey Piegza.
"It shows how much the market relied on this plan", she added, expressing concern that the project, adopted in a few days, might come "too late".
"If this project is really doomed . . . , the baton will be immediately passed to the Fed and other central banks to stoke the crisis, further tightening credit conditions", warned Brian Bethune, chief economist at Global Insight.
And stressing the urgency of the situation, Piegza noted that in the United States "every new day brings the downfall of a financial institution".
After the collapse of Washington Mutual on Friday, the authorities arranged for Wachovia Bank's banking activities to be purchased by its rival Citigroup.
In Europe, the crisis has taken a sudden turn and called for urgent intervention in favour of banks in the UK, Benelux, Iceland and Germany, suggesting that markets are facing 'not just an American crisis but a global crisis,' added an FTN Financial analyst.
The bond market has risen sharply.
The 10-year treasury bill yield dropped to 3,632% from 3,827% on Friday night, the 30-year yield to 4,161% from 4,357% the day before.
Obama won points in his first televised duel
After Friday's first debate between the two candidates in the White House, the second debate was held to determine who among John McCain and Barack Obama won.
The Republican and Democratic campaign headquarters were not surprised when both declared victory in a televised duel that was watched by a third of American families.
Political analyst David Gergen believes that John McCain's performance, however decent, was not "brilliant" enough to allow him to halt, five weeks before the presidential election, the decline in opinion polls.
Gallup, whose opinion poll released Saturday puts Obama five points ahead (49% to 44% for McCain), says the Democrat is the one who won the duel.
Among the undecided voters who matter, Obama is the winner for 39% of those polled, while a CBS poll puts McCain at 25%.
Obama should be able to confirm his leadership on Thursday with the expected performance of his running mate Joseph Biden in his first and only public debate with his opponent Sarah Palin.
"It would be a mistake to underestimate her.
She's gifted", noted Bill Clinton, however, about the weekend.
The 70-year-old McCain has consistently highlighted his undeniable experience in foreign policy, while also highlighting his opponent's "naivety" on the issues that were at the heart of the first encounter.
"It seems Senator Obama has failed to understand that"... was the repeated charge.
"I don't think Senator Obama has the experience and knowledge to be president", he added.
That's the offensive spirit that's been going on since last night's Republican TV commercial.
Obama, on the other hand, insisted that he was the future.
He didn't lose his head and he proved to be concise and precise.
He highlighted his ability to make good decisions and restore the good name of the United States to the world.
"McCain still doesn't understand, while Obama does", a Democratic commercial responded over the weekend, blaming the Republican for not taking the impact of the crisis into account enough for "the average American".
"In the 90-minute debate, this John McCain guy had a lot to say about me, but nothing about you", Obama told a crowd of 20,000 at a rally in North Carolina yesterday in a downpour.
He didn't even say the words "middle class" or "working class". Financial decay clearly benefits Obama, who the Americans see as more likely to save an economy on the brink of collapse.
"Next week could be a watershed moment", predicted influential Democratic Senator Charles Schumer yesterday.
Democratic Representative Rahm Emanuel, a former member of the Clinton administration, compared Obama's "economic foresight" to that of Bill Clinton during the financial crisis of 1998.
For the Democratic candidate, the current disaster is "the final verdict of eight years of bad economic policies as implemented by George Bush and as supported by Senator McCain".
The Illinois senator reaffirmed that despite Wall Street's unexpected jumps, he should be able to reduce taxes for 95 percent of Americans, and also pointed out that realizing the country's eventual energy independence by promoting renewable energy sources is his number one priority, along with introducing a health insurance system.
McCain, on the other hand, plans to build a park of 45 nuclear power plants by 2030.
Both candidates have carefully avoided questions about the $700 billion bailout plan passed by Congress last night, which is highly unpopular.
"What, did you notice there was an election in Minsk?"
Young people and opponents of the regime demonstrated on the main square of the Belarusian capital on Sunday evening to reject the results of the parliamentary elections.
Several hundred Belarusians gathered on Sunday evening immediately after polling stations closed on the main square in Minsk to protest the irregularity of the parliamentary elections.
Although no results have been announced yet, many young people have come to demonstrate against the regime of President Lukashenko: "dictator, resign".
Some admit that they did not even vote: "What's the point of doing whatever they want with my vote anyway", says one youth.
He does not believe that the regime, which has been friendly to foreign observers in order to resume negotiations with the European Union, is ready to make a turn towards democracy.
Sanctions, including visa bans for 40 Belarusian leaders and asset freezes, could be lifted if the election is deemed clean by election observers.
According to the opposition, it was not.
"We were kept away from the election commissions and our observers were not allowed to participate in the counting of votes", complained Yuri Potemkin, spokesman for the Union of Democratic Forces, a diverse grouping of 12 parties.
"It is a cosmetic change", stresses Alexander Milinkievich, a former opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential election and a leading figure in the pro-European movement, "because who counts the votes is important, and in our country it is the executive.
If any opposition MPs get into Parliament, it will be by being nominated, not elected.
Their entry into parliament, however, may mean television space, regional meetings and draft laws".
The opposition therefore feels obliged to participate in the political process because "a dialogue with the European Union is needed.
Because if our economy, deeply indebted to Russia, is hit by a crisis and we don't reform, we risk becoming a Russian protectorate.
But we want to be independent".
The opposition is concerned that the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which has been monitoring the election, will not declare the election valid.
It stresses that turnout appears to be too high and that the widespread introduction of early voting (26% of voters in Minsk) has opened the way to all possible manipulations.
"Did you notice that there were elections?" asks Social Democratic leader Alexander Kozulin, one of the last two political prisoners released in August this year.
"There was not a foot in the polling stations.
And there will be no more than five opposition MPs in Parliament, those who are most in line with the regime".
The night silence has once again filled October Square.
On television, President Lukashenko and members of the Central Election Commission congratulate each other on their success.
Conversation - Blood That Is Sure Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted that Héma-Québec had become one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he has regained the public's trust, which was seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
It is well known that the national blood bank administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In response to this drama and a wave of public disapproval, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, presided over by Justice Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to recommend that such a disaster not be repeated.
While Judge Krever delayed in delivering the report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood administration system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee took on this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, to manage Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company to supply all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec began operations in 1998, only 38 percent of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system", recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
Through our continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood products and our continuous work in this area over the years to come, we have rebuilt public confidence", he says, proudly adding that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population had trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is a very fragile thing".
The principle of prudence has been applied by Héma-Québec since its creation on 28 September 1998.
"At that time, we were seeing many cases of a human-like form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease", says a woman who has been running the company since its inception in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could be spread through blood.
We therefore based ourselves on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, which states that, where we do not know and where there is a risk of spreading a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterised by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusionary measures should be taken.
So in April 1999, we refused blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Then, a few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that the precautionary principle made sense".
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which directly detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood rather than the presence of antibodies on which previous tests were based.
NAT tests have shortened the deaf period between the time a patient is infected and when our blood tests can detect the first viruses, explains the specialist.
We've managed to shorten this period to less than a week.
We've reduced the risk of some donors getting infected without them knowing and without us knowing.
This improvement has made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of contracting HIV-tainted blood.
"In other words, it would take 12 million blood products to be distributed before someone could become infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission via a blood product is detected.
I think we can now safely receive or prescribe blood transfusions needed for healing", says Héma-Québec's chief executive.
"The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogenic element might show up in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus, like the West Nile virus, was discovered on Réunion Island and is transmitted through the bloodstream by insect bites.
"We need to be vigilant at all times", she continues, stressing that Héma-Québec must not only have a secure supply but also a sufficient supply.
"Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has implications for the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of eligible Quebecers".
Any healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the eligibility criteria but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who donate blood are not accepted because they have, for example, AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where the mudslides are common, they are banned for a year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
The flaws are very rare.
However, the number of members of the donor network should be increased in proportion to their age and to the extent that they are no longer able to donate blood.
However, persuading people to donate blood is difficult, especially when it comes to keeping and encouraging them to become regular donors.
Life is so unrestrained today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood", sighs Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also operates the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
The umbilical cord, once considered biomedical waste, is now teeming with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the deposit of our first 1,000 cord blood samples a few weeks ago and expect to collect over 1,000 a year.
We should start offering them for transplantation early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it", because Héma-Québec does not have the resources to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
Soccer - Impact in the semifinals
Impact Montreal qualified for the semi-finals of the USL First Division knockout round yesterday at Saputo Stadium in the second and deciding game of the quarterfinals, with a 3-1 victory over the Seattle Sounders.
The midfielder Antonio Ribeiro scored the decisive goal in the 90th minute of the game.
