Charest is betting on the north.
The Prime Minister has not ruled out calling an early election before the end of the year.
Immediately after the Liberal Party congress, Jean Charest moved to Jean-Talon, Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is running in today's by-election.
"Remove the boundaries of our last great northern border": this is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented yesterday in a visually compelling way at the conclusion of the Quebec Liberal Party Congress in Lévis, without giving any details.
During his speech, pictures were projected behind his back in a sort of picture mill.
There was a loop of three huge screens with remarkable images of hydroelectric dams, down, Quebec from Google Maps, maps, etc.
Generous funds, just like the election period.
At a press conference, the prime minister refused to rule out an early election in the fall, although he did note that he has a very busy schedule.
The "Plan Nord" is the fourth dimension of the Prime Minister's vision for Quebec, a vision of a "new economic area" that includes a labour agreement with France, a Canada-Europe Convention and an agreement with Ontario.
Despite the opening up of the North - the Northern Territory at the 49th parallel - the Prime Minister has often mentioned in his statements recently, it has never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, merely explained why the North is a "jewel of enormous potential", but did not give a timetable, the amount of investment or a clear priority for future projects.
He mentioned at most a few approaches to the points that could be further diversified: in particular hydroelectric power plants, forests, but above all the mining sector, encouraged by the rapid growth of developing countries and the renewal of public infrastructure.
The North, Charest's list says, contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamonds".
This "area twice the size of France is here", is in Quebec.
And it's not just with us, it's in us", he stressed, as if to show that he was invoking a certain national founding myth.
Quebec was built largely in relation to the North, the Prime Minister pointed out: the Abitibi gold rush, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
"It's ours, it's our future", he added after theatrically silencing himself to look at the huge map behind him.
The north, 70 percent of Quebec's territory, includes part of Labrador, which Quebec has always claimed, the premier said during a press conference.
"This is a traditional position that has been repeated by all previous governments.
There is one boundary line which has long been without a convention and if the opportunity arises, I will take this position again on behalf of the government", he indicated.
Otherwise, "we also need to rethink our vision of the North in the context of climate change", he said, referring to the north-west passage that will open year-round as a result of melting glaciers.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister believes that taking territory becomes a duty.
What about the inhabitants of the land, the indigenous peoples and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially the young.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (a former Pequista member of Parliament from Ungava), have already started negotiations with some 30 communities.
The Interministerial Committee, chaired by Benoît Pelletier and with Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) in a key role, launched the work.
The prime minister does not rule out a big meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment when "a shared vision will be outlined".
The development of the North should, moreover, be in line with the principles of sustainable development.
The North Plan will be "co-designed, structured and environmentally friendly", he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as a seamless continuation of the vision of the Liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
"Like the liberals before us, we have changed our minds to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development".
That was one of the more heated topics of the weekend, which kicked off Friday with a big cocktail celebrating the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's rise to the party's leadership.
One of the resolutions passed proposes to rename the Beauharnois plant to the Adélard-Godbout dam.
"From Godbout, who founded Hydro-Québec, to Lesage, who led the Quiet Revolution and nationalized hydroelectricity, to Bourasso, who created James Bay, our party has been able to shape the future", said Jean Charest.
At the press conference, he referred to another authority, this time a conservative, and that was the "Roads to the North" program of John Diefenbaker, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
When it came time for the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam, Charest stressed that its commissioning is scheduled for 2012.
"Just between us, but I plan to be there", he told his membership, prompting a standing ovation.
The same Prime Minister who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008 and no doubt in 2009 did not rule out the possibility of calling elections this autumn, which is allowed by law.
However, he stressed that his agenda was full, especially the Federal Council's mission to China and the Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend's convention provided the Liberal leader with a platform for some nationalist resolutions, in particular certain "attempts to amend the constitution", which passed very smoothly: the PLQ (Liberal Party of Quebec) specifically demands recognition of "the specificity of Quebec" in the constitution.
It also wishes Quebec to appoint a section of the members of the Canadian Broadcasting Council who would have the right to veto decisions taken in Quebec.
The opposition was skeptical of the North Plan in its main features.
The leader of the PQ (Parti Québécois) Pauline Marois has reiterated the Northern Quebec Development Policy launched by the Landry government in 2001.
According to her, when the Liberal government came to power in 2003, it abandoned the implementation of this policy.
If she had kept her word, "we would have gone on today", said Marois, standing next to her Jean-Talon candidate, François Mercure.
ADQ said they would support the adoption of the Plan North in the government.
"But we hope it is not just a theatre", explained Sébastien Proulx, the leader representing Maria Dumont, who is returning from holiday today.
Letters - The Unhonored Land
It was Vic Toews, former Justice Minister in Harper's cabinet, who dared to say last summer that Louise Arbour was a "disgrace" to Canada.
To humiliate a woman who has fought tirelessly for justice and who deserves all our admiration in this way says a lot about the Prime Minister's entourage and Stephen Harper himself.
We have a government that is the only Western country that has not deported a citizen of its own country from Guantanamo Bay.
A government that ignores the fact that Omar Khadr was a teenager when the crimes he is accused of were allegedly committed.
The only government that, despite Canada being a signatory to the Geneva Convention, is denying its word and letting a child soldier rot in inhuman conditions.
The only one that relies on a mock trial to determine the defendant's guilt.
Recall that UNICEF, Amnesty International and especially the Canadian Bar Association are advocating for Omar Khadr's repatriation to Canada to await a fair trial.
The same government is turning a blind eye to torture: it cares little that this young man is now psychologically destroyed, and no doubt permanently, after so many years of torture.
We may not realize it, but we are witnessing a creeping erosion of our rights, our freedom and our "democracy", words that Harper so proudly uses and that come out of his mouth so empty.
The time has come when there is no morality: it is possible to torture a Canadian citizen, to mistreat him, to imprison him at the whim of the head of a minority government (as it will be after October 14...).
Many voters believe they can find salvation in a party that preaches Virtue, Law and Order: they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr. Toews, is in this renunciation, and nowhere else.
Opinions - The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter was printed by Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Barrick Gold, a Canadian mining company.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has filed a defamation suit against three authors and a poor little publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate" and demands $6 million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truth, especially in the case of defamation, but the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver completely ignores this essential distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to conduct a public debate to bankrupt anyone who dares to take a different position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will be forced to spend a respectable sum of money to be prepared to defend and fight a very uneven battle with an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic in these unbalanced battles often involves bankrupting the defendants in order to secure a settlement that will silence the other side and, moreover, frighten anyone who dares to take up the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, they should have put their views on the whole thing out there.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate is normally an exchange of ideas, not a whipping.
So the mining companies were not satisfied with just opening their books, opening their documentation and setting up a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent scientific teams that could shed light on the whole thing.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to lack public confidence and has been ruthless in rejecting petitions and letters in support of the Noir Canada authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
It seems that in the vice president's world, that word only refers to the high-paid lawyers, not all Canadians; that's a pretty narrow definition of the term.
In a democracy, even the lawbreakers have a right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the case, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant is to be silenced (in its prosecution of "public debate", Barrick, by the way, has just issued an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to officially notify them to stop using the term...).
If we leave aside Garver's surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university's freedom to investigate and seek the truth, which is fundamental to any democratic society.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual activity.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that are not popular with the rich corporations of the world without being subject to repeated prosecution, who else can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have had one if it followed the scientific standards that the authors of Noir Canada use.
He's entitled to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debate and disagreement and resolve conflict.
Barrick Gold's overblown lawsuit makes it clear that despite what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it's time for governments to put in place measures to curb this type of unwarranted prosecution.
Operation to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally agreed yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the $700 billion plan to contain a financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular for: better control by elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money deposited, new measures to capture the number of houses seized for non-payment and also the right to monitor the salaries paid to managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican House Majority Leader Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news yesterday just minutes after midnight, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in markets", said Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson.
"Everything was done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the crisis that is now taking place on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"That's the bottom line: If we don't do this, the trauma, the chaos and the disruption to the American everyday life will be huge", said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the past few hours, negotiations have been going to maximum speed for fear of the effect another failure would have on investor sentiment.
The deadline was for the markets to open this morning.
Both candidates for the US presidency were invited to negotiate later, and both spoke more in favour of the deal, but without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited the amendment to the agreement with some measures, in particular the one aimed at allowing homeowners to keep their homes and the wage measures for the heads of state-bailed-out companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is no need to congratulate them.
But these measures are necessary", he explained on television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so".
"The rough features I have read [show] that it is something we all will have to deal with and move on with.
Choosing to do nothing is simply unacceptable", he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to use taxpayer money to buy back dubious claims and risky and unsellable assets of U.S. financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then moved to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA), and resulted in a cash freeze and the collapse of banks and financial institutions.
The failure of last week's first draft of the agreement is on the Republican side of the House.
Once the Democrats have accepted that some of the "toxic" assets of troubled companies will be only guaranteed by the government, not bought, there is a belief that a dead end is being avoided.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, a provision was added that would allow the government to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it had to take losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan calls for a first payment of $250 billion, with the possibility of an additional $100 billion if the president sees fit.
The additional $350 billion must be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in the rescued companies, which will pay dividends if they make a profit, and which it can sell again when it's all over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the impoundment procedures for loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The plan's makers would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it's not clear if their plan will be greenlit.
Yesterday, the vote against this bill continued to rise in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's obvious Washington can't hear you", Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money off taxpayers is not the answer".
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, moderator of a congressional group dubbed the "Skeptics Committee", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred respected economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us asking Congress not to rush too far and to carefully consider the way forward", he said yesterday.
At the same time, Europe has reaffirmed that this crisis is a global crisis.
Following the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
