Paul Newman (1925-2008) - The death of a socially engaged icon
His beauty with his blue eyes had long been his trump card, others said his weakness.
Has this American actor with a charming smile escaped narcissism?
Yes and no.
His shyness, his sensitivity and his unrelenting talent also kept him from the power category that breeds true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at the age of 83 at his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the "fat years" of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, to whom he was similar and long a rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was of Hungarian descent.
From these European roots, one of the most famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without the over-the-top ego, which is the ultimate mark of quality.
Because he was the face of this entire country in love with a self-made man, a war veteran in the Pacific, wounded in battle, who studied acting at Yale in the early '50s, went to the Actor's Studio in New York, and celebrated triumph in theater, television and, eventually, film.
The same civil rights activist was also a race car driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans and a sex symbol, despite having been a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
And with it, the shadowy places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the noise of her own show business, which will forever remain somewhat mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend has caused film buffs to feel dizzy as his big roles compete on the dark screen of memory.
It's been a parade of more than half a century of ever-changing American seventh art.
The charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Tin Roof, a 1958 adaptation by Tennessee Williams, reemerges in memory.
From a more recent past (1990) we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not live up to all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Rocky Graziano, the repressed, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role originally intended for James Dean, taken over after his death, which brought Newman to real fame in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, Oscar for best picture in 1973.
The bitter and vindictive billiards player in Robert Rossen's amazing The Hustler (1961), he would play the same character in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which would earn him his only Oscar of seven nominations in 1987.
This face that's been traveling for ages, that was him.
And he did.
He's had a career that's been a rivalry between different eras.
Young people know him best from the cult classic Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) as Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen brothers.
He then closed his career playing the Irish mob godfather in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike a few film legends who left the business fairly soon, Newman remained in the business long after, though he denounced Hollywood for its glitz, glitz and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier, not without humor, considered it "a lively challenge to underplay", judging that he was pushing the envelope too hard in his performances.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom roles came like a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
But he played first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, thugs and desperados, whose declines and rebellions were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed the little-known side of his shy sensibilities.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian author Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, presents a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
He dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son to his son Scott, who died of an overdose.
In a tribute to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former fellow fighter Robert Redford (the two starred in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) lamented, "His presence made my life and this country better".
Generosity, love of life, these are the main qualities of a deceased actor.
If we leave his legendary career behind, we also leave a great civil rights activist, environmentalist, independent filmmaker, anti-Hollywood decadence.
We were used to seeing his image on bottles of vinegar, sauces, cookies, and other foods, which might have seemed rather tasteless, although it was a gag at first.
However, the proceeds from the sale went into his Foundation for Troubled Childhood.
So, rather than be swayed by fame, Newman stayed involved in the community until the last minute.
He left a letter to his five daughters that included these words: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful for his happy planet.
It was an honor to be here".
And it has been an honor to follow the career of such a visionary and generous American artist.
And, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced at the Zuschlag & Co. invoicing factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial will begin in the criminal case against János Zuschlag and his associates.
The politician and his accomplices are accused, among other crimes, including forgery, of a long-term and systematic fraud by a criminal organisation, which has caused exceptionally significant damage.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, they used the money raised in public tenders for their own purposes and often used fictitious invoices to prove their tasks.
The money from the state and local governments - some 65 million forints in total - went partly to the treasury of Fiatal Baloldal and partly to the pockets of individuals.
The methodology also reported by the Office was that the money raised in the public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration and the commitments made were never received by the association.
According to the prosecution, a large portion of the invoices were forged.
The forms for these invoices came from the market in Józsefváros, the round stamp was made in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of the companies in which the invoices are to be produced were decided, among other things, on a circular route along the northern shore of the Balaton, on which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
According to his statement, the first appointment was to look for guesthouses and restaurants.
In these documents, he requested invoices for his consumption, which were then used to produce invoices submitted in public tenders drawn up by, inter alia, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of the Capital respectively.
The invoices were mostly issued by István Lados with his partner András Őr, who according to our information wrote most of the reports needed to obtain the subsidies.
On his "study trip", Lados saw a basement.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its partners in 2003, the establishment catered for a group of 90 members of Biztos Pont.
But the company executive said that so many people would not be able to fit into the facility at once.
The invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later to Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was also full of formal and substantive errors.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms, and more than ten people could not sleep in it one night, yet the bill listed 130 guests.
However, the imaginative printers went too far when they listed a company also engaged in hospitality, Pigal s.r.o., whose accounts did not even contain documents bearing the names of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá, according to information provided to the Public Prosecutor's Office.
Győző Farkas, the head of the company, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he knew immediately that they were fake documents.
"Our business name and tax number were on the stamp in the wrong place".
He added that, in addition to formalities, the fact that they accommodated 100 people according to the invoice was also not acceptable, since they only have 11 rooms, which do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, the invoice also listed the food, and their restaurant has not been operating for a long time.
The eager invoicers were also not convinced that the prominent Budapest travel agency only organised international trips and mistakenly listed the cash-only invoice as a travel agency in Hungary, which was also inconsistent with the company's invoicing practices.
Moreover, as was revealed during the investigation, VAT was also mentioned in the document, although the organisation of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
In the four documents issued to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation by Hotel Révfülöp s.r.o., Hotel Révfülöp s.r.o. also disagreed with the amount of VAT, since the company's activities are not subject to the 25% VAT rate but to the 15% VAT rate, and the hotel staff only issued printed invoices, but the invoice produced was handwritten.
Moreover, the 'issuers' distorted the invoice, for example by stating that one company was carrying out, as revealed by the investigation of the Public Prosecutor's Office, a road haulage activity which the company originally based on investment advice did not carry out.
The fact that the invoices issued to the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért foundations and to the XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont associations are false was also revealed by the formal deviations - the incorrect format of the invoice and the incorrect stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna K.S. or the Kunfeherto Sports Camp, whose representatives denied that they issued the invoices.
For example, the counterfeiters did not notice that HIB s.r.o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001) when it was catering to a group from Fiatal Városért, which is why, according to our information, the company's liquidation commissioner also denied that he had issued the paper.
They're knowingly issuing invoices.
The second group of invoicers is those who knew they were to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation has issued accounts for around HUF 4 million for the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták organisation.
The head of Collab s.r.o. was, according to the indictment, induced to issue a fictitious account by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Biogate s.r.o., currently in liquidation, also cooperated with Zuschlag and its partners and supplied the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and the Atlasz and Vörösfenyő associations with invoices worth around HUF 5 million in 2003, which were not actually economic.
Nor the movement of money, because the invoices generated were later cancelled, which the organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
The other group of invoicing firms included those with ties to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was an authorised representative of the Ukrainian manager of Delta Trió s.r.o., a company engaged in the trade of fuels and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, but not located there.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment worth approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the information obtained by the investigation, these invoices were purchased by Cash Investment s.r.o., a company in Kiskunhalas which was in liquidation as of 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian man to whom, between 2002 and 2005, Ivan Kubatov was also alleged to have handed over documents related to the company.
As we know, during the investigation, Kubatov admitted to issuing invoices on behalf of the company to the associations Atlas, Hoppa and the foundations Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért and to accepting their consideration himself.
The Romanian masons established Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s.r.o. and Jos-Investment k.s. specifically at the request of Ivan Kubatov.
In fact, none of the companies were working, according to the defendant, because they were not getting jobs.
Nevertheless, the undertakings were in favour of him, since, at the request of his co-defendant, Zsolt Szente, who also drew up their instruments of incorporation, he issued invoices on their behalf to the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció, which were affiliated to Zuschlag.
On behalf of Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov has issued a total of 15 invoices to the organizations, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecutor's office determined that Kubatov had obtained 10 percent of the amounts shown on the invoices and VAT.
The man also used Szi-Beri k.t. to issue fictitious invoices, this time for the Biztos Pont tender.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség and Modern Magyarországért associations submitted proposals to the public tender of the Mihály Táncsics Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organisation of the Socialist Party.
They each received 500 thousand forints, but they did not use the amounts for the purposes set out in the proposals.
To avoid this, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team s.r.o.
These invoices were found during a search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
During the trial, some of the defendants will likely describe the process of producing invoices, as they did at the prosecutor's office.
What may be more interesting is if the main defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to reveal everything himself.
His testimony so far is not very detailed, and although he has promised several times to explain everything in detail, he has not done so yet.
The question is whether it is in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, 50 million forints, maybe the Socialists have made a deal with him and Zusi will take it.
He could have been offended, for his requests for a reduction in the conditions of his detention, namely house arrest, have so far not been heard.
While economic offenders who have committed much greater damage and have not yet paid for it can walk around freely or at least wait for the end of their proceedings in their homes, he does not have that option.
The psychology of bullying: Why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overpriced goods.
The neurological and economic underpinnings of this familiar - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed by researchers at New York University's Department of Neuroscience and Economics.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to fall behind in eBay-style auctions, so they pay too high a price.
Researchers have used an experimental auction to try to map out the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a simulated auction, and functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) was used to examine the active areas of the subjects' brains.
In both games, the participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the important element is to beat the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively when the loser lost.
This area of the brain plays a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system, among many other functions.
The researchers therefore believe that the price escalation can be explained by the effort to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the members of the research team of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional study.
Three groups competed against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, the other group was promised an additional $15 reward if they won the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but if they lost, they lost that money too.
So the difference between the two groups was that one group was emphasizing winning and the other group was emphasizing losing.
However, the members of the "loser" group were willing to go higher than those in the control and "winner" groups, confirming the neuroscientists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any pre-existing economic theory.
They have so far explained the phenomena of winning and risk-avoidance.
Neural imaging has helped us resolve the discrepancy between the two theories, and we have now come to a third explanation", says Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Some half a billion people worldwide have chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is listed as a leading cause of death.
The estimated number of domestic cases of hepatitis is 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
Although the symptoms are similar, with hepatitis and jaundice being the most common, the causes and the diseases they cause are different.
Depending on the source of the disease, hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should in any case protect themselves by vaccinating against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after eating an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, stomach problems, and vomiting.
Then, the skin and eye whites will turn yellow, the stool will lighten and the urine will darken, and the treatment may take two to three weeks.
Each year, a million people worldwide die from the more serious form of the disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that only one in ten infected people is estimated to be receiving medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver or liver cancer.
Most people who are infected are unaware of their disease, and the disease destroys liver cells in a subtle way, so the first symptoms often do not appear until 20 or 30 years later.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening are very important.
Three groups of people are much more common than average: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory tests, a person should contact his or her doctor if he or she experiences any symptoms of unknown origin.
If detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, and infectiousness and cancer can be prevented.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first celebrated globally in 2004 by organisations representing the sick.
It aims to draw attention to the chronic hepatitis caused by these viruses, its causes and the importance of early detection.
Who believes in God, doesn't it hurt so much?
According to recent research, faith in God acts as a kind of painkiller that may have eased the death of already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to examine how belief in a god influences a person's perception of pain, reports Britain's Telegraph newspaper.
In a rather bizarre study, they subjected 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists to electric shocks while all of them were looking at a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to eliminate much of the pain.
A technique that examines the human brain in detail has also shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The research is the first in a series of studies involving academics as well as scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The test was carried out with precision by attaching a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the subject that gave electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to look intently at two paintings: Sassoferrato's 17th-century Virgin Mary and Leonardo da Vinci's 15th-century Lady with an Arch.
The authors hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of piety in believers, whereas da Vinci's painting was chosen because it is not too different from the first and, they say, has a soothing effect.
Subjects spent 30 minutes in an MRI scanner and received 20 electric shocks in four successive sessions while separately viewing a religious or general-themed image.
Catholics reported that looking at the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "taken care of", and "calmed down, filled with peace".
They reported that when they saw a religious painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the study, believes that any highly impressive image can have a similar effect on atheists, as long as the right photograph is found.
"We need to find an image that they will see very positively, from the mother's or father's perspective", said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the study.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases change our personalities", Wright added.
After such excellent results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the pain regulation of the faithful if they were shown a Madonna by Leonardo or a painter of similar calibre.
Would looking at a quality Virgin Mary mean even better results?
You are what you give
On its tenth birthday, Google can say that people can find it in their pockets at least as easily as in the sky above them; they know where they've been on vacation, what professional exams they're taking and what they're interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, that's still not enough.
But for the skeptics who are drawing parallels with Orwellian darkness, the very nature of Web 2.0 is not clear.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about its users, which is necessary to keep up with the original goal of the founders: "Let's organize all the information in the world!"
According to a confessed Google official, after ten years of world-class work, the company is still at the beginning of its ability to handle all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "what should I be doing tomorrow?" or "what kind of work would I be doing?" - seemingly simple questions that software won't be able to answer until it knows enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that the exact words they search for are captured during the Internet search, as well as the IP address from which the search was made and the pages to which the searchers have moved after the search.
The Personalized Search service, launched two years ago, allows users to save their browsing history, look back at what they searched for and clicked on, and in the long run generate results that are more tailored to them. The Recommendations service will also be based on the same logic, offering products and services based on previously stated and stored preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I'm doing? - users who are afraid of Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the scope of the potential power represented by the company is more intimidating, the backlash does not evoke guilt, fear of punishment, a desire for freedom or even rebellion against power in Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that all search terms are not only intercepted but can also be released to a third party in justified cases, in which case the privacy rights of internet users are not protected by law.
Perhaps the most famous recent example was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that allowed the identification of pedophiles from Orkut community sites it had set up.
But Internet users who are concerned about privacy rights were given a break in May when the company, along with the electronic rights organization EFF, successfully proved its case against the FBI: Google must not be forced by any article of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI in the future.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully recovered nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had obtained by invoking a strengthening of the Child Protection Act passed years ago, but it still failed to obtain lists of individual user searches, or complete lists of websites and keywords spanning a two-month period.)
The view of Google is thus quite contradictory: it is whipped by those who are afraid to give their personal data away because they feel that their privacy and privacy will be compromised by starting to use Google services, and they are speaking out against it with a revolt that belongs to multinational companies with a conservative image.
And yet the American geek culture and its wild offshoot, a group of enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users emerging in many countries, see him as the next generation of big business, the "corporation that's thriving now", unlike its rival Microsoft, which is seen as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, even though they're both fighting for the same goals.
This may be because, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require its users to provide an identification code or to pay for its applications; an open, free and constantly fresh source of information and software packages seems much more accessible, younger, 'cooler' than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks have a very good understanding of the very problematic relationship between the Internet and privacy rights, which has brought about one of the most talked about buzzwords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Because Web 2.0 is nothing but collaboration, about intentionally leaving behind footprints and using the channels of communication that we have at our disposal, and although the scope is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show up.
The average young person can maintain a profile on a few community sites from Facebook to Xang, which can easily link to other services like Twitter or the last.fm app that records the music they listen to, all of which can then be linked to navigation systems like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and they can also write a blog that automatically shows their latest photo gallery that they upload to Flickr or Picasa.
There are many examples of this happening: a friend in the morning can easily see a flood of photos of mutual friends and figure out who her wacky boyfriend spent the evening with, or a company can fire an employee simply for posting their honest opinion about top management on their blog.
The one who lives the online life is made up of what he shows himself to be, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least avoid Google's monopoly, has a choice (starting with Scroogle, which uses Google's search engine but deliberately leaves no trace).
For example, a lot of people deliberately don't register on community sites so they can't be found, and Google's online apps, from text editor to photo editor to news portal, can be swapped out for alternatives that aren't connected to huge server parks and don't build the best profile of us.
Public opinion is not too secretive about waiting for Google to show its teeth.
The company, now worth $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense ad space is jeopardizing advertising agency investment, and the ever-accelerating pace of service introduction is seriously upsetting not only Microsoft but many other software designers.
Critical observers, however, find some disturbing counterpoints: for example, top management's total rejection of employee protests after doubling the company's tuition fee, the company's view that any frequent meals were too expensive, all of which are lost on Google's 2006 submission to the Chinese government, which, under its agreement, filters any findings that are in the good taste or interest of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal rules is that it never advertises new services in advance, only when they are ready to use, but what is certain is that the expected problems of the coming months and years may take the world to new places: while some believe that Google's project to scan and archive books and magazines is growing to such an extent that the company will soon be facing the US Supreme Court, others are terrified of its Health system, where we can build our own complete health profile with previous findings, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can then serve as a good starting point for future generations of science fiction writers, and Cory Doctorow's famous novel "Scroogled" describes in Orwellian terms a future where humans can only be intimately approached with Google data.
