The Warsaw Stock Exchange has made an offer to buy the Prague Stock Exchange
Two hundred million euros - about five billion CZK - was offered by the Warsaw Stock Exchange for the purchase of a 100% stake in the Prague Stock Exchange.
Ludwik Sobolewski, chairman of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed the offer made by the Polish side even though the Czechs had previously excluded the Warsaw Stock Exchange from the range of possible new owners of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason is the fact that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is owned by the state.
99 percent of the shares are held by the Polish state, which wants to sell 60 percent of the securities in a few months.
According to the Czech economic daily E15, the offer from the Poles is the highest amount ever offered to a bidder for the Prague Stock Exchange.
According to Czech newspapers, bids have so far been submitted by the Vienna Stock Exchange, the Transatlantic Nasdaq Stock Exchange, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse.
Last week, the head of the Prague Stock Exchange, Petr Koblic, said that the Warsaw Stock Exchange would be the worst new owner of all the prospective owners, and he did not rule out that this could lead to the demise of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague Stock Exchange is estimated by stock market experts at 5 to 10 billion.
According to the shareholders' agreement, approximately 90 percent of the shares could be sold.
The largest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is the investment bank Patria Finance with a stake of approximately 25%, followed by Česká spořitelna with 14.7% and Tiger Holding Four S. a. r. l. with 13.5%.
