A smart car mimics the flight of a bumblebee
What better way to develop technology to prevent collisions than to mimic obstacle detectors found in the natural world?
For example, in bees.
The initial strategic idea for a surprising project, presented at the CEATEC trade fair in Japan, was inspired by the Nissan bees, and it was to build a new generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed a BR23C-type biomimetic robotic steering system, a robotic mini-car that is equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is actually very similar to our safety protective cover", explained Kazuhiro Doi, the brand's general manager of technology PR and research and development.
An important factor is the folded eyes that allow bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of over 300 degrees.
To mimic the function of the compound eye, engineers have come up with the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 metres in front of BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an anti-collision operation.
The obstacle is detected in a fraction of a second, and then the robotic car starts mimicking the bee's movements and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision, it instantly changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this escape maneuver is performed in a completely instinctive manner.
"If it weren't, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, because this technology fits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process should not take more than a blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, this movement cannot be upward, downward, or transversely oriented, but can only be two-dimensional and only in a direction that allows the wheels to rotate.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees for avoiding, the robotic car has only the option of rotating, accelerating and decelerating.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifetime than lithium-ion variants.
Ando says that what's important is instinctive, intelligent response, not processing ability, let alone data storage.
This mechanism shall only process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
It doesn't need to store them and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few kilobytes of memory at a time.
It doesn't need gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step towards developing an instantaneous avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could be in mass-produced cars within 10 years.
Another application could be to connect the unit to a GPS satellite navigation system, which would guide the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles in the road.
