The bill for a $700 billion bailout package to be split into several installments to buy back subprime loans from banks is now in writing.
Half the money will be used in the first round.
After further talks that ended after midnight on Saturday, congressional officials reached an agreement in a days-long debate on a $700 billion bailout, Reuters reported.
"We've made significant progress", announced Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the House, who said the only thing left to do is to draft a deal.
The compromise package was also supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Commenting on the outcome of the compromise, Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said: "The program will work and be effective, but more needs to be done".
The written package was released before the Asian markets opened at 8pm Washington time on Sunday (or 2am Central European time on Monday), but did not trigger any major stock market rally.
The bill, the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, which is to establish the program, will be voted on Monday by the House of Representatives and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and news of the deal was welcomed by the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and highly appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The program, by the way, differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which was to spend $700 billion at once to buy back subprime mortgage-backed securities.
Now, the first round of spending is now limited to half the $700 billion, so that $250 billion will be spent immediately after Congress is expected to decide on Monday, and the Treasury will use it to buy mortgage-backed securities that are rated as subprime, and the fate of the remaining $100 billion will then be up to the president.
The program will be overseen by a special committee, including the chairman of the Federal Reserve.
Spending the second half of the $700 billion will depend on what Congress decides next.
The Ministry of Finance may, in accordance with the law, use a combination of tactics: it may simultaneously buy back sub-prime loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other 'toxic' loans.
The buy-back can be done through auctions or directly, the ministry said.
The legal provision will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme whereby the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee of funds giving cause for concern, for which the company will pay a price corresponding to the amount of expected losses.
As Henry Paulson said, the act provides the means to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it be to buy up large amounts of bad assets, insure them, or prevent the systemic risk of a major financial institution collapsing.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed", he added.
Instead, bankers who are in trouble and waiting for government help can expect a government reduction in their severance pay - simply called a "golden parachute" in overseas slang.
The reduction in their salaries will only be in certain cases and will depend on the type of aid provided by the Ministry.
The restriction essentially means that if the department buys at auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on the gold parachutes unless the fallen bank directors are sent straight to retirement.
In the case of a direct buy-back of substandard loans, the government will act aggressively to ensure that management money is not overspent.
It should be added that the existing Golden Falls contracts will not be changed, the restriction only applies to new contracts, which is intended to be a further incentive to participate in the programme.
"This is the first time in American history that there will be a legal limit on CEO compensation", commented House Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank, a Democrat.
Moreover, the State will be entitled to a share in the participating banks, reducing the risk to taxpayers, as once the economy and the rescued bank are back on their feet, they can also profit from the transaction.
The plan calls for the president to submit to Congress a bill within five years to determine how taxpayers can recoup expected losses in the financial sector.
There were, of course, voices on both sides of the debate about the plan.
"This is not what the American people asked us to do, because this is not going to protect taxpayer dollars", said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
His fellow Democrat from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes the passage of the provision was pushed by the very people responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in industry increased by 0,1% in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12,9% compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
The export sales prices of the industry were 1,1% higher compared to July 2008, decreasing by 3,9% year on year.
The manufacturing industry prices were 0,7% higher as a result of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, up 3,2% year on year.
Domestic sales prices in industry increased only marginally compared to the previous month, by 0.1%.
Domestic sales prices in manufacturing also increased slightly, by 0.1%, compared to July.
The largest price increases were in August 2008 in the leather and footwear sector (2,8%) mainly due to the month-on-month price increases in the manufacturing of leather goods and silk products by 4,6% and footwear by 2,5% respectively.
The higher price level of plastics and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly price increase in the chemical materials and products production sector (1,6 per cent).
Prices fell in the oil processing sector (1.4%), electrical machinery and equipment manufacturing (0.9%), as well as - to a lesser extent - in the woodworking sector (0.1%).
Prices in the papermaking and publishing and printing sectors remained unchanged.
In the other manufacturing sectors, we have seen price increases in the range of 0.2 to 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sector, which has a large share of domestic industrial sales, prices increased by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the continuation of the officially agreed increase in gas prices since 1 July.
In the 12-month comparison of domestic sales in the individual manufacturing sectors, prices increased most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4%).
The metalworking sector saw a price increase of 13.2%, while the food, beverage and tobacco sectors, which are the most important, saw an increase of 11%.
Prices decreased in the textile and textile products industry (2.5%) and electrical machinery and equipment industry (0.3%).
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price growth ranged between 0,6% and 9,1%.
Overall, manufacturing prices rose by 10.2% over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sectors were 18.7% above the previous year.
In terms of breakdown by sector, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) in August in the sectors concerned by the production of tangible assets.
Prices in the consumer goods sector increased by 0.3%, while prices in the energy and further processing sectors remained unchanged on the previous month.
The largest price increases compared to the same month of the previous year were observed in August 2008 in the energy processing and further processing sectors (16,8%).
In the consumer goods sectors, we saw a 6.8% increase in prices, while in the tangible assets sector, we saw a 1.4% decrease.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in HUF increased by 1.1% in August compared to the previous month, decreasing by 3.9% on a 12-month basis.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7% against the euro, then by 7.1% against the dollar in one month, rising by 7.5% against the euro and 15.9% against the dollar in August 2007.
