The economic collapse of the United States has been felt by journalists, as the newspapers are in a period of investigation, and many blame the Internet, the killer of the press.
The Pew Research Center asked 500 journalists about the state of their profession and their predictions for the future.
Well, today, almost all journalists are pessimistic about their future.
However, respondents did not openly say that they had less concerns about credibility.
They don't feel as isolated as they used to.
The problem for American journalists is money, the money.
For these journalists, the 2008 crisis is a crisis of a broken economic model.
Besides, the cuts made in the newsroom, the room where the editors work to put together the paper, are a huge problem.
According to the journalists interviewed, this is a problem that needs to be solved if we are not to see a fundamental change in traditional journalism as it is understood by the general public.
American journalism is permeated by a clear but complex pessimism.
Six out of ten print journalists and senior executives believe that journalism is going the wrong way nationally.
In the local area, the executive team is at 65%.
Printed against broadcast.
It's not hard for a journalist to see where the web is going.
The major publishers are making their way to the Internet, which many view as the "killer" of print.
The "economic pressure" that journalists are pointing out has increased by as much as 79%.
Five hundred journalists interviewed admitted that they resort to technology in the hope that it will "do something good" for their journalism.
The biggest gap in American journalism is between those who run newsrooms -- that is, executives -- and the reporters who work for them.
56% of national leaders are confident that their reporters share their values, while at the local level, the value drops to 23%.
This has something to do with job security for someone.
The national rate of managers who think they're going to lose their jobs in three years is 47%.
As for the journalists, they're moving to 30%.
As for the "sure work" of the staff in America is still the order of the day.
Only 13% of journalists work on contract.
In a nation as vast as the United States, with 300 million people and thousands of newspapers, magazines, radio, TV, and the Internet, employers often offer what they want, and so it is a take-it-or-leave-it question.
Executives are almost always paid huge salaries, and the editor can earn as much as ten thousand dollars a month, not including pension and insurance.
As regards holidays, the argument is complicated: a certain number of days after the first year, a certain number of days after the third year until 15 days after a certain number of years.
But American journalists, by their own admission, often fall ill within a year.
It's just a matter of climate.
The trial in Rome, Daniel Coppola, is in progress in Grottaferrata.
The president of the second criminal chamber of the Roman court, Carmelo Rinaudo, has decided to reject the application of real estate entrepreneur Daniel Coppola, who asked to be moved from his hometown, Grottaferrata, to an apartment in Rome.
Coppola is under investigation for bankruptcy in connection with a counter-offer to sell Unipol-Bnl.
During the trial, at his own expense, he was released last week from house arrest, which was converted into a forced permanent residence in Grottaferrata.
His lawyers, Michele Gentiloni e Gaetano Pecorella, have asked that the real estate entrepreneur be allowed to move his residence from a rural town to the capital.
However, according to the court, this move (which the PM has spoken out against) would allow him to influence his company and gain access to the evidence that accuses him.
The Elites in Danger
This phenomenon was already evident a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout plan put forward by the White House: a large part of the American people were more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times report that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old soul on the East Coast, more moderate, friendly to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which is conservative, hostile to those in Washington and the financial world, strong especially in the Midwest and the South.
A soul that has shown itself arrogantly by voting, as I mentioned at the beginning.
But this thing that I just quoted is just one example of the changes, the big changes that the current economic earthquake is already showing: not just in the United States, but all over the West and maybe not just here.
In both the US and Europe, this crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator for phenomena that have been in incubation for a long time, that are solidifying in a new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the reactivation, the extraordinary revival of the market, the dual category of State power in relation to a certain re-nationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which of course have strong links abroad, but which are mainly concerned with the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
Which also created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the problems and protests of people and families, which are voters, among others.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be largely out of the picture or to have little to offer: the European Union, which is as always divided between different interests and different national strategies and unable to decide on a common political line, has given clear evidence.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual country, the bailouts, the market revival, the new rules and, most importantly, the allocation of funds: the moment we get into a crisis, only countries have the economic means, the amount of financial resources to be able to try to fix things.
And they also have the necessary means and the authority to use them: two sources of immense value, in certain circumstances, which perhaps no market or international organisation will ever be able to use to a similar extent.
This new emphasis on the national element, which the crisis places on the national dimension, is in line with the increasing emphasis on the one factor closely linked to recent economic progress: territorial integrity.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the sieve, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, out of nowhere we realized that our future would instead have to contend more and more with such few immaterial things as water, grain, oil.
All things, who would have said, can be moved from one place on earth to another, but in any case they are connected, absolutely, to a limited space, a territory.
So whoever becomes their ruler has a lot more cards up his sleeve than whoever isn't and who has the misfortune of living in a place with no grain, no oil and no water.
I'm getting to the second news item, but it predicts a breakdown.
When you talk about territory, state, government, you're inevitably talking about politics, which is leadership.
In view of the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to be emerging.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritative leadership, a request for someone who can take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, there is a wave of discrediting of existing leadership, especially economic leadership, which has proven equally inadequate and full of dark spots.
And together with that something even deeper and somewhat disturbing: the discredit, the impatience, the sense of incompetence and absence that is trying to control the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
For it seems that there is a growing belief among the broad masses of the population that their actions are not the same as the ideas of the up to now popular elite, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite are out of date and indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership simply feeds off a branch from the underground, but a powerful movement to remove the ruling classes and the traditional political order is manifested in sudden electoral "resistances" or unexpected shifts in collective mood in recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the fall of Labour in Britain to the uprising of US Congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligence, some would say their format, are having increasing problems understanding, that is, representing, what, not today, is being created in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is intensifying again, growing, potentially too dumb.
Before this, it would be too much to talk of a permanent "mass uprising".
But we can't say that it means keeping our eyes open.
Super glue for walking on walls
Overcome the laws of gravity with super glue and in the future walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the object of various American research centers, and now a team of four institutes is getting very close to it.
Scientists have managed to keep a 100-pound body glued to a vertical wall with a sticker just one inch [2.5 cm] square.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, the University of Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material that the research team has invented is an evolution of existing materials that use a special structure of carbon called a carbon dwarf tube.
"The glue base can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The researchers were inspired by the gecko's legs, which are covered in microscopic hairs that allow the animal to achieve perfect adhesion.
Tests on materials such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper showed that the new glue is ten times stronger than the reptiles' legs and "just sticks off the wall", explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be useful as a temporary glue", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe walking on walls like Spiderman? Maybe, but researchers are thinking of a far less fascinating use as a connection to electrical devices, because dwarf carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering .
No superheroes at this time.
OTHER RESEARCH  The University of California, Berkeley, is also researching a new glue.
In an article in the journal American Chemical Society, California scientists described a glue made of microfibers like hair that cleans itself of dust by moving across a surface to maintain a perfect fit.
Medicines: never with juices
Watch out for grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
If you take these drinks, which are consumed mainly in the summer because they are refreshing and full of vitamins, along with some life-saving medications, their consumption changes the potency or decreases the potency with serious health consequences.
To highlight the dangers of juices, both fresh and finished, when combined with certain medications, David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, is sounding a new alarm at the 263rd National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia: One glass of grapefruit, orange, and apple juice is enough to reduce the absorption of some lifesaving drugs, negate their beneficial effects, and put patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been accused of being responsible for increasing the effects of some antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antihistamine, and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
THE MEDICALS AT RISK The Italian Medical Agency itself announced this in a newsletter two years ago, urging doctors and patients not to underestimate the dangers of this mixture and to be careful about what they drink when taking drugs, such as Diazepam or Methadone.
Not only grapefruit  Experts say that orange and apple juice also contain substances that suppress drugs.
A long list of effects of grapefruit and other juice.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the pharmacology department at the State University of Milan: "Such discoveries are usually immediately reported to various international and national pharmaceutical agencies, which may arrange and exchange information manuals for medicines.
So always read the package leaflet of any medicine you buy, and if you find anything unclear, do not worry but ask your doctor or pharmacist for clarification", stressed an expert for Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in economics is going to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize was awarded to American Paul Krugman for his studies of commercial models and localization of economic activity.
Krugman is a 55-year-old New Yorker who teaches at Princeton University and who is a well-known editor for The New York Times.
Krugman is one of the most important critics of the Bush administration's foreign, economic and political moves.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, in the days of Enron's collapse, Krugman predicted in a commentary in the New York Times that the second event would be far more important than the first in terms of its impact on the history of the United States.
A prediction that has caused much controversy and been blamed for years, but has proved to be accurate.
"I'm surprised and shocked at how quickly collapses like Enron and Worldcom have disappeared from the public eye", Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenz Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is "an economist of great importance" but also a popularizer who has "a very aggressive style, particularly critical of the excesses of the Bush administration's liberal policies".
Open Office, we have the third edition of the anti-Microsoft package here.
Today is the release of Open Office.org 3.0, an open source personal production suite that aims to penetrate more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the more popular Microsoft Office.
After about a year of work by volunteers, controlled by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is being presented to the general public with various new features: the welcome screen and the revised and improved opening window are complemented by other, far more substantial features, such as compatibility with the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest standard version of ISO.
The emphasis is also on cooperation with Office 2007, Open Office is able to open a document with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Some models have special features, such as the ability to reduce the size of a PowerPoint presentation, for example, for electronic transmission, or the ability to transfer a PDF file to a graphical design model and maintain the original appearance of the page.
Still from this perspective, we can create "hybrid PDF" documents that resemble typical Adobe graphics and have the characteristics of a spreadsheet or word processor.
Collaboration is an element that has received many improvements within application programs: in excel it is possible to work together between different users and avoid conflicts on changes, in the text program each collaborator is assigned one color to the comments to be more clearly identified in the revision phase.
Some companies are also working on bringing some of the Open Office features to the web, and they should be able to present a final result in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html, and has been added to the English version available on Mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual the package is also available for the Linux operating system.
The installation CD can also be sent to your home or workplace on request.
And if the topic of free of charge can be a catalyst for expansion in the home, it is the commercial area of Open Office that the package is very much focused on, and it can already count on a variety of projects being implemented in public administration and schools.
There is also a range of training, consultancy and assistance services ideal for SMEs, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main models: Writer, for video writing replacing Word; Calc is a spreadsheet processor that aims to replace Excel; Impress for PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase, as in the case of the more famous Access, is a program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, finally, is a graphical model.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that we are now almost at 3.600 thousand, with the release of the new version, it is possible that this projected number may even be exceeded.
