The New York Times asks, is Italy racist?
Italy "as a country of emigrants has only at the last house become the first destination of immigrants" received with reluctance.
So asks a long article in the New York Times, which focused on the debate over racism in Italy, starting with the case of a young man named Abdul William Guibre, originally from Burkina Faso, who was killed last month in Milan for stealing a box of cookies.
This case illustrates what the New York Times calls the "paradox of the North": the northern regions are also where "more integration and more work" is recorded, but also "the strongest anti-immigrant sentiment in the country and the strongest support for the Northern League".
To confirm the rising tensions between Italy and immigrants, the NYT cites cases of intolerance from Milan, Parma, Rome, Ciampino and Castel Volturno.
Not just that.
Legislation demanded by the Legislature to curb immigration and facilitate the expulsion of illegal immigrants is also cited as an example of the changing climate in Italy.
A trend highlighted by both the Pope and the President of the Republic: "Giorgio Napolitano, after meeting Benedict XVI in the Quirinal, asked that the State and the Church work together to defeat racism".
Students who are victims of expensive rent - up to 900 euros per room
The rental market for college students is not in crisis.
According to the latest research by Sunia, a rental union, a student can rent a single room for up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has already reached such proportions that entire classes of students have lost their right to study because of the overall high prices their families would have to bear  explains Laura Mariani, head of Sunia's study office  in this city, high demand from students has distorted the market in such a way that it has triggered a process of price increases that have spread to residents".
In most cases, the lease offers contain several infringements: free-standing, unregistered, unlimited lease, associated sub-leases.
For Sunji, an exceptional intervention is needed that could regulate prices through tax reform.
If we look at the details of the research, we see that in Milan, in the Brianza area, the cost per bed is around 450 euros, with a single room ranging from a minimum of 650 (in the Bande Nere area) to a median of 800 (in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera areas) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria area).
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350-400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the university, a bed in a double room costs 250/280 euros, while a bed in a single room costs between 370 and 500 euros.
In Rome, in the central university areas (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), they want around 600 euros for a single room, 450 beds in a double.
The figures are slightly lower (EUR 550 for a single bed) in areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
The only way to save is to move to the outskirts: 300 euros per bed and 450 euros for a single room in the Prenestina, Centocelle and so on.
In Naples, beds cost between 300 and 450 euros, rooms between 400 and 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, they want 250-350 euros for a bed, at least 350 for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are definitely lower, but they have a greater impact on the citizens' economy.
In cities such as Perugia, where the most common phenomenon is renting for students from outside the European Union, another anomaly is finally being noted: an increase of around 25-30% in the fees they charge for international students, compared to Italian ones.
Goodbye to the old Paradiso Cinema, the cities are tearing down historic theaters
The historic movie theaters are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without a cinema is like a blind man, like a face without eyes".
The image, presented by director Giuseppe Tornator, successfully documents what is happening in the big Italian urban centres as well as in the rural towns.
The process of curbing cinemas, the birth of large multi-screen cinemas in the suburbs and the subsequent demise of monastic halls in the central areas of cities is one of those events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the hallmarks of a true cultural crime.
Often, historical sites are lost, full of memories, "it's like losing a friend, a friend with whom we shared a journey and a lot of emotions", says the director of the New Paradiso Cinema, a film that won the Tornador Oscar and the Grand Jury Prize at Cannes 20 years ago, and which told the poetry of a village cinema and the grief of a way of life that cinema has probably lost forever.
The figures obtained by Anec, the main operator association, speak for themselves: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, with the highest bills paid mainly by theatres in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna was the first with 82 cinema losses, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And proof that the rise of multiplexes is primarily responsible for their disappearance is that these three Italian regions have the highest number of new multiplexes: 195 more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 more in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
The Italian process has developed irrationally says Paolo Protti, president of Aneca, "it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones survive, because when one cinema in a city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to a multiplex.
Let us not even talk about the lack of funding for the fund for operators: the previous state debt is around EUR 10 million.
From a moral and ethical standpoint, it is a shame that the government does not respect the existing laws.
The sector would need between EUR 16 and 18 million a year to support it.
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to have concerns about closures and to have decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Aneca, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in the historic centre and in the suburbs.
The planned standards include tax relief measures in favour of operators and mobility benefits for the public: spectators will be able to drive into restricted traffic zones and will have special prices at stops and in some parking lots.
I like this initiative says Giuseppe Tornatore"and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by introducing other measures.
But what is certain is that in order to counter the great power of multiplex, traditional theaters must improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
Defending traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: closing the Super Cinema in Bagheriya, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to start the "New Cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I walk past the Rialto or the Quirinal on Rue Nazionale, which are now closed, where I've shared so much emotion that I don't have to look at the black and dusted signs, I turn the other way.
Link between politics and the 'ndrangheta mafia, Mayor Gioia Tauro in prison
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to manipulate the municipal election to suit the interests of the Piromalli mafia group".
The charges brought by the Directorate for the fight against the Mafia in Calabria against the Mayor and Vice Mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione e Rosario Schiavone, and the Mayor of Rosario Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external collaboration with the Mafia organization, are heavy.
Also in the handcuffs are Gioacchino Piromalli, the old mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his grandson, a lawyer, the boss's namesake, already accused of committing crimes of a mafia nature, sentenced to pay 10 million euros.
"They ignored all legal and moral norms, as well as common sense", prosecutors wrote when two local governments expressed their willingness to pay for consultations with Piromalli's lawyer.
"This would allow the mafia group to enter the city's official administration and facilitate the already enormous possibilities of control and management of the public administration".
Agazio Loiero, president of the Calabria Regional Commission, makes it clear that "there are many secret agreements between local institutions and the organized criminal underworld in his region: "There are areas where the mafia is more concentrated than in others, where secret agreements are inevitable.
But we also have many local politicians who resist the pressures of the 'ndranghet, heroes who are still untouched".
This morning's arrests follow the arrests of last July, which police said showed that Piromalli's mafia group had been given a final blow.
Since the end of April last year - the Gioii Tauro city council was dissolved in 1991 due to the then-presumed link between organized crime and the local administration - local politicians have been removed from municipal office.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, chairman of the Christian Democrats, who at the time of the dissolution was elected head of the centre-right coalition after a narrow election in May.
He was shouting about the scandal when the prefecture ordered the city council dissolved.
He called in then-Deputy Interior Minister Marc Minniti and accused him of plotting the whole thing for political reasons, but the judges in the arrest warrant signed this morning explain that the mafia group even went so far as to request a change to the A3 highway project.
Further interrogations ordered against Dal Torrion, the prosecutor writes, revealed "a willingness to shift the claims of a businessman, a representative of a larger group very close, as is commonly known, to Piromalli and to adapt the elections of the public administration to the interests of the mafia group".
When energy is born from waves, the big ones come into play.
It's an endless deposit that covers over 70% of the Earth's surface and is now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides, tides are new sources of inexhaustible energy, which have caught the eye of giants like Chevron, which is now trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of generating energy from the sea has been studied for over a century, and research intensified in the 1970s in the wake of the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil dropped around 1980, the idea of using offshore power went away, but now environmental organizations and the new increase in oil prices have given the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London in 2007 stated that about 15 percent of the world's electricity consumption could be covered by harnessing the movement of the waves.
This amount would be twice the energy currently produced in nuclear power plants.
And then there's the currents and the tides and the tides.
The giants are attacking.
The company that invested in offshore energy was Enersis, which agreed in 2005 to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When this plan was announced, it seemed like a huge revolutionary step.
After two years of investing in marine energy, more and more companies are investing in marine energy over traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology", a spokesman for a company linked to the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and they're considering working with us".
The cooperation we're considering involves obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to get a marine energy project up and running in Alaska.
This signal cannot be underestimated, especially when you consider that Alaska is where the U.S. continues to drill for oil and recently President Bush came up with a plan to drill again.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also following the offshore energy trail, and the amounts invested so far, although not known in detail, are showing increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology that needs to be developed.
Experts say the technology is still in its infancy because the environmental impact of using marine energy is unknown.
So far, the facilities in Portugal and some in Scotland are small and do not appear to be causing major problems for the ecosystem.
However, to produce more energy, it is necessary to use technologies with a greater environmental impact.
The methods are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boats that are interconnected.
The wave force that moves the buoys up and down is converted by the cylinders and cylinders into hydraulic pressure inside the buoys.
It's pushing the turbine, which feeds the power to the generator.
Power is being brought to shore by undersea cables.
So far, four of these devices are in the design phase, pending federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for military purposes.
In contrast, Verdant Power is already generating power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six offshore turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water during high tide causes turbines to spin, which in turn feeds the generator.
Verdant said they have a long list of clients waiting for the necessary authorizations to use this energy.
Waves, tides and waves.
The potential for tidal activity is of particular interest at this time, says the Electric Power Research Institute.
Although they are not related, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves and thus more reliable as a source of energy.
In fact, states like New York, Maine, and Alaska, along with other coastal states, have already invested $7.5 million in tidal energy in 2008 and are forecasting up to $35 million in 2009.
